Web Application Firewalls (WAFs) are excellent at catching script kiddies but remarkably fragile against a sophisticated attacker who understands context-aware encoding.

This article demonstrates how modern adversaries bypass signature-based and ML-based anomaly detection engines by utilizing polymorphic payloads.

```javascript
// A highly simplified example of payload obfuscation
let a = 'con'; let b = 'structor';
let payload = a+b;
[][payload][payload]('alert(1)')();
```

The key to bypassing is understanding the exact normalization process of the target WAF. Does it resolve specific HTML entities? Does it parse multi-part form boundary anomalies? By finding discrepancies between the WAF parser and the backend server parser (HTTP Desync), an attacker can slip malicious queries right through the defense perimeter.
